         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">10/8/80 ¶  ¶ In answer to your question, dear Sir Joseph, I would just mention, that I noted Batis as Halorageous in my "select plants" ¶ B76.12.04, p. 31. See M to J. Hooker, 25 April 1880, and J. Ho...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">80.08.10</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller 1871-81, ff. 285-6.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; "/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation by Hooker: 'And Oct 1/80'.</p>
               </note>10/8/80</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In answer to your question, dear Sir Joseph, I would just mention, that I noted Batis as Halorageous in my "select plants"<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B76.12.04, p. 31. See M to J. Hooker, 25 April 1880, and J. Hooker to M, 10 June 1880.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>; the Indian (<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">enlarged</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>edition) you will doubtless have got from Calcutta direct.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B80.13.07; see p. 43 and also systematic index added to this edition, on p. 372.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>In addition to supplying M with copies of B80.13.07<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>he distributed from Melbourne (see for example, notes to M to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>W.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Odgers,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>17 April 1880,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>M to E. Behm,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>6 May 1880); there is<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>also,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in private hands,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>a presentation copy inscribed by M to David Gaunson dated May 1880.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The Government of India also distributed copies within India and to other colonial administrations: for example, to Singapore and Ceylon (now Sri Lanka) (register entries recording letters acknowledging receipt in British Library, Archives, India Office records IOR/P/1507 Agriculture and Horticulture, Part B, proceedings. p. 34) and Straits Settlements (National Archives of India, New<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Delhi, Home, Revenue and Agriculture Department, Part B, Agriculture and Horticulture Branch, proceedings, July 1880,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>nos 99-100).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>It may be best to keep it as a distinct order, but it seems to me to have its best place at all events near Halorageae, especially as the development of albumen of the latter is so very variable and holds not good for distinction in most other orders[.] You seem to have over looked Grisebach’s notes in the Flora of Brit. West India, where he puts it with Salsolaceae, after Kunth.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Grisebach (1864), p. 61; probably Kunth<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1822-5), vol. 1, p.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>479.</p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>over<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">underlined; vertical line in margain</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">and</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">MS annotation by Hooker against</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>looked … Brit West India<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>: 'No! They contain nothing to note'.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My Material on Palms is very scanty, but I will send you what I have. In North Queensland the palms (even there like Bamboos)<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">not</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>numerous) occur in fever-jungles beset by cannibals; indeed I rather meet a tiger or Naja<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The generic name of the Cobra.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in India or a lion in Africa, than savage bipeds in the forest-recesses of N. E. Australia. Travelling moreover is expensive here; but if the Exhibition-duties<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M's duties in connection with the International Exhibition, Melbourne, 1880-1.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="2"/>are over I am likely to go to N. Queensland for a few months, to study palms &amp; other plants needing local elucidation.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M never made the visit.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The financial depression affects us all here also now more than ever, and with increasing debts of the colony &amp; alienation of crown land and unproductive buildings &amp; exhaustion of mines the prospects are not cheering! especially in a Department like mine, which is ruined almost totally already.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The postscript paragraph that follows is on a separate folio (286) that appears to belong with this letter.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">I send once more 89 &amp; 91 of the fragm.,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B78.11.04; B80.02.02.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as they contain notes on palms: Ptychosperma Normanbyi is stoloniferous.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Kentia minor<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I have referred to Bacularia<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M described<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Kentia minor</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in B74.09.02, p. 235, but referred it to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Bacularia minor</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in B78.11.04, p. 58. Drude ... henceforth<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">is written in both margins, with positions indicated by asterisks.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(Drude intends in justice to acknowledge<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Bacularia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as Beccari also will henceforth), a genus sufficiently established before Wendland’s. The spikes of B. minor are intrafoliaceous, therefore those of a true Bacularia &amp; this species (unlike B. monostachya) is stoloniferous also.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Bacularia minor</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Bacularia monostachya</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Batis</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Halorageae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Kentia minor</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Ptychosperma Normanbyi</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Salsolaceae</p>
         </div>
